caption: Visited Awadh for my birthday with friends! Excellent service, delicious food and good ambience. Totally loved the cocktail and kababs. Malai kofta was super rich and appetizing! Recommend awadh if you want to try some Indian food with a little twist! Will be visiting again soon!
Good food with good service.
Excellent food, a must try
I simply love their food. I always get excellent customer service here. The place is always clean and the workers are always super friendly. Would recommend to others.
Great food with quality ingredients.  Had a friend come into town and she asked me to take her here again.
One of the best spots on UWS!! Great staff and food!
Could be more organized.
This was one of the finest fine dining restaurant near time square,I celebrate my birthday dining,stuff r so friendly,
The rice was aromatic, the chicken curry was delicious and the five spiced vegetables were delightful.
Overall an average experience. Ambience and food both were just okay
The bill won't shock you. Menu is like a cafe in Indianapolis I loved.

I like to go with friends to this restaurant with my warmest recommendations. I visit this place often. I get very good feedback from my friends. The the cooking is delicious and the crew is efficient and cooperative. Whenever we go to this place we have a gorgeous time.  warmly recommended.
Visited on a Thursday. The service was very welcoming and observant. Prices were reasonable. They have so many good reviews for a reason.
Stopped in on a Tuesday. The service was very welcoming and observant. Prices are fair I would say.
I went here with my mom and sat outside, had great service and the food was yummy!!
Beware. This location is closed, but through the internet they will take your order and deliver food to you from the Upper East Side.

I have heard great things about this place and want to support a local restaurant but people should be aware that we ordered our food at 5pm and it is 6:45 and we still haven’t received it. We live just a few blocks from the restaurant- almost 2 hours seems too long to wait.

PANDEMIC BAIT & SWITCH  This otherwise amazing restaurant has decided to dupe their customers in to thinking the food (during this pandemic) is being prepared in their restaurant but they are instead passing along your order to another Indian restaurant on the Upper East Side called Moti Mahal Delux (1149 1st ave) and then having it delivered by taxi to their restaurant. This is shameful and frankly dangerous as there are so many opportunities for secondary forms of contamination to enter our food, we don't know the source of where it's coming from and frankly, it's totally dishonest. Awadh should be ashamed of themselves. Just shut your restaurant if you cannot make the food yourself. You are not a commissary and customers need to be treated honestly especially at the prices you are charging
The menu and service were beyond our expectations. We surely enjoyed the atmosphere of this place. Extraordinary spot to take my family out for lunch.
Lamb Saag here is a taste of heaven. Also very friendly pick up. Looking forward to dining in after COVID-19 shutdowns
Food was fantastic, mean was really tender and flavorful

Cauliflower appetizer was lovely, as was the okra. Chana masala was nice. I liked it. I will go back. That said, there are other places I like better. Maybe it's just a style difference between NY and Houston. Would give 4.5 stars if I could.

If you want to relive Mughal era, visit Awadh. Only place in entire US to serve Galauti Kebab. Raj is awesome as ever to guide you and make your evening a memorable one. Must visit if you want to experience Lucknow in New York.

This was my 3rd visit to this restaurant and I was so disappointed that I decided to write this review. We ordered Murgh kali mirch and sufiana Murgh Biryani. Both the dishes were flavorless and totally Americanized. Murgh kali mirch was no where close to what we were served before. The chicken was far from tender which is the key to Awadhi cuisine. The dish was overloaded with heavy cream, was under salted and I did not sense even the hint of black pepper. On biryani, I am totally speechless. All I could taste was saffron, no hint of garam masalas which is one of the main ingredients to any biryani. Needless to say that they are only catering to American clientele unfortunately. The food they serve is no where close to the Awadhi cuisine as they claim.
Nothing special but more than adequate. Food is good and so is the service.
Amazing authentic taste. Must have indian food - rare balance of spice to flavor ratio and genuine service. Keep up the fantastic work. One of our new favorites even though it's far.
Outstanding. Make sure you order the gulab jamun for dessert.
The best restaurant in upper west side

I’ve thankfully had Indian in many places but nothing compares to the level of quality that Awadh in the upper west side lives up to. I shamelessly have order their paneer masala countless times and have never failed to be amazed. Highly recommend.

Yummy indian food
Excellent food.
I eat here a lot since I work in the area. I must say the customer service is always great and they keep the spot neat all the time. Pricing is convenient and they serve sizeable portions.

Ordered delivery. Took them over two hours. They kept telling me a different story about why it was delayed. Then the delivery guy told another story when the food was finally delivered. The food was ice cold when it came. They told me they would give me a refund but never did.
Beautiful inside. They were also helpful with my Postmates order.

This restaurant is my number one place.  Of all restaurants I know I like it most. I never miss an opportunity to go to visit this restaurant. Whenever  I want to go to a delicious meal, this is the place that comes instantly to my mind. exeptionalgorgeous and all kinds of  food and a rich cuisine.great crew, and nice mood. And very important, the charge is reasonable. I praise this spot with great pleasure.

Man where do i start. The food was bland. One of the dishes we ordered, the chicken 65, had no salt, no flavour, and we had to send it back. The whole place was smoky from lack of ventilation. Our eyes burned and felt irritated from the smoke the entire time we were there. An utterly nightmarish experience at such a highly recommended place.
Amazing chicken masala and fried okra
Tried this place before with a friend and I am hooked ever since. I love the fantastic mood and delicious food and drinks. Kudos.
Coconut fish curry was amazing. Chicken korma was great.
Wasn't all that great... We went on a sat for lunch .   Food was average. Had better.
So nice

Being from Lucknow and have eaten the real galouti kabab from tunday kababi. galouti kebeb from awadh was tasteless and the quantity was nothing but a joke, 3 coin sized kebeb for 13$. biryani was not also authentic Awadhi.
Amazing food, great service

Amazing food near Columbia University! My go to for Indian food. Slightly expensive, however, totally worth it. If you are vegetarian, tell them to make you 'Kadai Paneer'. Must have for Indian food lovers

I'm a neighbor. I get the stench and the noise from the vent fan that they left on AGAIN. It's almost 3 am. Some peace and quiet would be nice so I could sleep but I guess those sleaze bags think that holding down the rat population is more important.
Amazing food. Nice staff

Cool modern hip place! A little on the noisy side, but food was tasty, fresh, and good flavors and levels of spiciness. You gotta love the Bollywood movies projecting on the wall as well. Get the samosas, poutine, and ghost chili vindaloo! All delicious!

TL;DR - The food is AMAZING, the service could be better. would definitely come again to try some more dishes. So we've been going to a lot of Indian restaurants lately, and this one probably has the best and most authentic food among them. It's also not your familiar Punjabi cuisine (butter chicken), so it's still Indian but somewhat different flavors than the ones you're used to. For starters we took the DALCHA PALAK KEBAB and the KAKORI KEBAB which were both great, and flavorful. The TARIWALA chicken for main was also a favorite with a sweet twist to it. We didn't care so much for the cheese desert. The waiter was not great. He convinced us to order more bread than we needed saying it was a small portion, and although we repeatedly asked for no cilantro or parsley garnish, it was there on almost all of our dishes.
Awadh is an Indian restaurant on Broadway. Uptown. A small restaurant, but very neat and great service. Good? Yummy... Delicious Indian food... Good for family eat out.
The menu and service were ahead of my expectations. I absolutely loved the ambience of this restaurant. Superb place to take the family out for lunch.

Went there for dinner on my birthday. Little skeptical as in most Indian restaurants food has become rich and spicier instead of genuine aroma, taste and flavor!!! To my surprise, Awadh still maintained the authenticity. Loved the  food and taste. Well balanced spices and herbs. I prefer this one over others in midtown!!! Must try!!!
Awesome food with authentic taste
(Translated by Google) Culinary experience to have.  (Original) Experiencia culinaria que hay que tener.
I tried this place before with a friend and I am obsessed since then. I enjoyed the good mood and delicious dishes and beverages. They never disappoint.

Everything was well spiced without an over reliance on heat. Cool to see a few unusual dishes on the menu, like slow-cooked broccoli. The okra entree was surprisingly good, especially since I don’t typically like okra. The cauliflower appetizer was my favorite dish.
delicious lamb biriyani, the main reason we go here. there were people waiting outside to get a table
Good food. Expensive.
Food wasn't terrible, service could have been better.
The restaurant is excellent and spacious, the menu was delicious and the rates were very reasonable. fast, productive service and very friendly waiters. I recommend this place.
They offer a large variety of delicious food. I liked dining here. Staff members are always super nice, pricing is reasonable and the place is always kept clean.
Paneer tikka masala is great and the butter naan was so fluffy and amazing! Everything here was great, including the service and drinks
The quantity of the food they provided was just hilarious. The galouti kababs cost a fortune, but they were literally coin sized.

Gaurav was my wedding caterer and I don't think I can stress enough how amazing he and his team were.  My husband and I got married a little less than a year ago, and to this day, our guests still rave about our food. Gaurav was extremely professional, and his food was AMAZING, he incorporated everything we wanted, and had great recommendations as well.  My dad who is very hard to please, to this day continues to compliment Gaurav, and constantly wants to throw family parties at this restaurant. Finding wedding vendors is such a stressful part of wedding planning, especially finding a caterer, but I have to say, having Gaurav be a part of our wedding was one of the best decisions we made.

Great Galauti kebabs which I am always on the lookout for. The Shikamporee Shikh was good if not perfect. Some good mutton dishes as well but the Rann was not as good as the Dahi Gosht. The kaali dal was the crowned offering for sure and you must order it with the perfectly turned out naan. The missing star is for the not so warm welcome we got when we entered although we had reservations. The service improved vastly over the course of the evening

This was my first experience EVER at an authentic Indian style restaurant. Okay so they start you off with some bread and 3 different sauces. If you like spicy you'll LOVE the green and red sauce. If you like a milder, sweeter sauce, then go brown. The chicken was so tender it practically fell apart in my mouth. Absolutely amazing. I really wish I was going to be up here longer, because i would MOST DEFINITELY return. Amazing place, amazing food, and an even more amazing, very well trained, thorough staff. Thank you for the hospitality.

Good food. Found it slightly overpriced as compared to other restaurants around the block. The spice level is toned down and they dont have options to increase it. The taste isn't close to authentic indian food
Good biryani! Good service
Loved the sweet potato-pineapple grilled appetizer. Service is great and a pretty well done interior and ambience.
Great food. Truly delicious. Should definitely try awadhi murgh tikka!
Great food, don't miss chicken Tikka, love it
Great food and good service. Make sure to try the fried okra, chicken tikka masala, and coconut shrimp.  Can’t go wrong with anything on the menu really.
Fantastic  authentic Indian taste .

Probably added in my top 20 Indian food places! Mango lassi is great than most of the restaurants (when it comes to the liquid thickness as it should be). The dishes are more artistic and thought about than Bhatti grill (same owner owns both restaurants)
Great Indian fares: also very friendly staff try to explain everything about food to me.
The food was delicious. We had the grilled potatoes and pineapple along with the fried okra for an appetizer. Some of the best naan bread I have ever had. 5 stars.
Inspired dishes, unique takes on classic cuisines. A must try!
Always love it! My go to authentic North Indian place :) Never fails to impress

One of the finest restaurants in NYC serving Indian food. If you are a vegetarian, this is the place to visit. Best Panner dish I had in a long time. Recommend to visit this place if you want to try authentic India food.
Solid Indian food in the UWS.
Great food. Good service.
Nice!!

For delivery: The food was cold, 45 minutes late and incorrect. When I called, I was offered $5 back on a $30. This is the 3rd time they've messed up my order. I would recommend never ordering delivery from here if you want to get what you ordered.
Excellent food, good service
Great food and prompt service. We loved the curry dishes. The cauliflower appetizer is a bit disappointing since it was too sweet. Otherwise a very enjoyable meal.
Excellent service, delicious food (coconut curry shrimp with Jasmine rice and naan, masala chai) and great atmosphere.  One of my fave places to eat out

This place was referred to me by a young sales rep I have just met, who claimed that he had visited India nine times. Gave a raving review. “Fit for foodies” Lousy service – non-responsive, having to ask several times for a sauce from the different waiters, busboys and a by-passing manager. And overall – Indian waiters universally – the most pleasant and personable waiters in the world – in my 40+ years of good food dining experience. Powerful noise from the kitchen (food processor? Wining pipes?)  This place serves very mediocre (at best) food (and for Indian restaurant to have mediocre food – is an “accomplishment” – with such an abundance of ingredients – it is not that easy). Drinks are there too – not thought out at all. In your face “exotic drinks” Mango puree stuck with chilies does not make it neither good nor exotic.  Essentially – I had some expectation. Not high – but some. Everything, but mostly food was below any expectation. Poorly thought out menu, I have to add.  Sorry. Don’t trust modern “foodies” anymore.

I love this place - this is one of the few places that has a great sit down experience but also delivers!  Very few North Indian places in New York do kebabs well and go beyond the regular "Tikka masala" staples - and this place is one of them. I would recommend getting the Galouti Kabab (minced, spiced, aromatic lamb patties) and Awadh Murgh Tikka (very tender marinated chicken baked in a tandoor)  The entrees I recommend are the Nali Ki Nihari (Curry with goat on the bone with delicious bone marrow inside), and Kofta Dilnaaz (creamy curry with cottage cheese and vegetable patties).  The reasons I'm not giving them 5 stars: 1. Their dessert selection is not great and they don't have the items on the menu half the time. 2. The host is a bit rude but it could just be a language barrier.  Food: 4/5, Service: 4/5

Anybody looking for incredible food needs to give this place a try. Let me say, I have never been to an Indian resturaunt prior to this experience, but I went with my partner for her birthday after a great deal of research. We settled on this place, despite some of the lower reviews that we discovered are completely unfounded. Having eaten at numerous Indian eateries, my partner raved about the quality and depth of flavor Awadh had to offer. I got the Methi Malai Mater and she got the Khaas Korma. Granted, we could have shared one with the lemon rice, but we wanted to try both and were oh, so rewarded. Please, give this place a try. You will not regret it. **2 dishes and a bread app came out to $51. High quality food with reasonable prices for NYC
Great place to eat authentic Indian food.
Amazing Indian Muglai cuisine! I have always all the meals here, the food is very flavorful. This is probably the best North Indian restaurant for me

Really amazing food here at Awadh. Virtually every dish I've had is packed with flavor and perfectly balanced spice. I particularly like their biryani dishes as they're not as bland as I often find biryani to be. Their service is typically very attentive and friendly, and the decor is stylish as well. Note that you will probably pay more than you would at your run-of-the-mill Indian restaurant, but it's worth it in my opinion.
Verry good

Love this place.  It's all vegetarian.  No menus.  You sit and they serve you buffet style bringing you item after item of all you can eat.  Loved it and if your into indian vegetarian than you must try this place.
Excellent Indian food. Elevated take on traditional dishes. Great service.
Top NYC establishment for northern Indian cuisine.  Intimate setting and excellent service.
A bit pricey, and service on a the slow side (a weeknight visit) but very nice food!
Great atmosphere, very good dishes and service.

2019 Update: rude service. Don’t go. I use to love awadh but the chirpy staff’s comments and lack of professionalism just simply don’t deserve your money. Disappointed to see a place with decent food have such rude service. Host in particular. This downward trend seems consistent given the other comments  Skews for an older crowd and pricy.  Moral of the story: much better options in UWS
Amazing food! Truly worthy of all the accolades they have won. Hands down one of the best Indian restaurant i have been too. Personally recommend the lamb chops!!
Fantastic Indian food.  Would definitely go back.

Made a reservation for 4 before going to the opera at Lincoln center. Food was really delicious. We had the lamb patties, samosas and 5 spice chicken skewers to start and the chicken Korma, lamb Biryani and coconut shrimp curry for mains. The biryani is not to be missed and all the flavors were amazing.
Excellent Indian food in a nice upscale environment.
Exquisite service and the best Indian food anywhere. Highly recommended.

The food is very good. Tha ambience is very pleasant. The Gilauti kababs were the best I have had in a while. Butter chicken was too sweet for my liking. Appetizers were excellent and so was the biryani. I took away a star for service. I reserved for a family gathering of 10 ppl. My 6 year old was with us. All of us were there on time. It was 45 mintues before we got a drinks menu...after repeated requests. It was an hour before complimentary papad was served...after 3 asks. It took an hour and a half before appetizers could reach our table. The salad accompaniment reached the table when we had almost finished dinner ( a no no) We skipped desert as it got way too late. Perhaps they need more help. I was saved any family ribbing for my choice of restaurant because the food was very good. We are a family of foodies.

Some of the best Indian food I've had, including best lamb chops called "Chaap Ka Barrah". Samosas and Biryani were also fantastic. One of my go-to neighborhood restaurants especially for special occasions. xo, Sally from NST Pictures
It's a nice place, the food and atmosphere is good. The portion sizes are decent
Good food but overpriced and the rice is separate from the entrees.
Great food
Excellent food. Keep going back for more! Keep it up!
Everything the best
Excellent food.   Fish was perfect.

Awadh has the upscale Indian menu I crave and atmosphere to match. Though the beer selection is pretty bleh with only bottles and no craft beer, just the standard mass market Indian brews, the cocktail list is pretty good. The food is awesome with a wide selection of appetizers, small bites, and entrees from vegetarian to seafood to meat. Service is alright if a little reserved, but everything came quite quickly.

Absolutely scrumptious cuisine with hungry man sized portions. First time I've eaten here, but I will certainly return. Not inexpensive, but quite reasonable when considering the quality and quantity of the food and the location.
Took 20 minutes to get menus, 1 hour and 10 minutes to get our dinner and the food was unfortunately not as good as we would have hoped.
The best Indian food I’ve ever had , this is a MUST if you are in New York area!
High quality Indian restaurant. Great service and food.
Delicious Indian food!! I got the chicken korma and it was incredibly yummy. Generous portions and great garlic naan bread! Do yourself a favor and visit this little gem.

If you are in uptown near 100, 102nd st and plan to eat Indian cuisine do visit this place. Decent ambience, delicious appetizers and entrees along with good options among Indian Breads which ranges from Roti to naan to Laccha Paratha's. Don't miss out their Indian Masala Chai. Bonn Appetite!!!

This place has the one of the best lamb chops in NYC period. The place in general is OK. We ordered following things: The  Nawab: Great Tamarind Flavor. Rating 4/5 Galouti Kebab: Very juicy and lamb was very fresh. It could have had some more spices but overall is was good. Rating 4/5 Shikampuri Seekh: Again chicken was very fresh and well marinated. Kebab was very juicy. Again some more spices and salt in kebab will just enhance the experience. Rating 4/5 Chaap ka Barrah: Best lamb chops in NYC. So juicy and full of flavor. Rating 5/5 Lagan ki Raan: Portion size was good and flavors were great too. The quality of meat they use is really good. Somehow I felt that salt was less in this dish. Rating 4/5 Khaas Korma: Great chicken dish if you looking for something with mild flavor. Chicken was very well cooked and was very juicy. Rating 4/5 Green Chutney: Most different green chutney I had in my whole life. It had very raw flavor of mint but nothing to compliment it with. There is seriously something missing in it. To make it even worse they add something sweet to it. Rating 1/5.  Overall the place has great potential and I would definitely give it another try.
One of the finest indian cuisine restaurants in nyc but SUPER expensive. The food was authentic indian. One entree is just good for 2 people.
Great Indian food with decor and service to match! The food took a little too long to cook and be served but that was the only issue.

4 people, walk-ins, great service, decor, and food. Prices were a little high.  Awadh murgh tikka $13, dum hare phool $14, kofta dilnaaz $14, 2sub veg biryani $15x2, a drink $14, and some extra white rice $3. $95.81  Pomegranate chicken was good, biryani were spicy, broccoli in sauce was great (very creamy).
The food was awesome
Nice elegant meal with friends
Michelin stamp Indian food! Delicious and not so expensive!

Went to Awadh for a special birthday dinner.  Not as we expected.  The cocktail The Nawabh's desc was Tequila, Lime and Black Salt.  It arrived looking very different.  It was Tamarind juice with Tequila.  No mention of Tamarind in the drink desc.  I sent it back.  Appetizers were good.  Entrees were extremely disappointing.  We ordered their specialty dishes.  Baby potatoes in gravy were sliced up large potatoes.  Chicken Korma and Baby Potatoes gravy was the same.  All the dishes we ordered were a soupy mess on the plate.  The gravy was thin and watery.  Mutter Methi Malai was watery and had no flavor of Methi. Very disappointing meal.  To end it all, they charged us for 2 bottles of wine (instead of 1).  Let's just say, we will not be returning.
Little pricey but above average food.

This place is a great choice for authentic Indian food. Ambiance and service on point! Quality and taste of food was excellent for the most part. Among the various dishes we ordered, kofta was a slight disappointment coz of the overwhelming flavor in the gravy and lack of the same in the actual kofta. Desserts were really good. Drink, appetizer, main course and dessert ( all sharing) will cost you an average of $50 per person.

By far most expensive Indian restaurant with nothing to defend ridiculous prices other than nice decor. Lamb shank dinner was basically a bone with meager scraps of meat in a bowl of gravy. Broccoli in cream sauce did not even register as Indian food on my palate.
Awesome food, best Indian food in New York.
I like this place. I used to like it better but they changed all their staff and now I like it less.

Decent Food. I come here for their egg curry which very few other have. Place is mostly crowded. Food tastes good. Some of the servers are rude.
Very good restaurant

We were 4 people and went to Awadh last week. We didn’t had a reservation but were given a table for 40 mins (6:20 PM) before the people with reservation arrives. We were rushed through our dinner to finish on time. Food was fine. Everything still felt fine but it was odd that they added a 20% tip by default. We were not even given a good service. I guess 20% is their benchmark to just serve food to the table.
Very delicious

Great food and ambiance. The food seems very authentic though the sweet dish menu was a bit disappointing and hence I took away on star. Had a great time with friends. Do do so try the Galauti kebab and awadhi chicken kebab as starters its awesome and will not be disappointed. We also had the dum biryani which had an interesting presentation and reflected the depth in taste the name suggested. Would love to go back and enjoy their delicious delicacies again a big thumbs up.
Great food and service. Their cocktails are not up to par (especially for the price of the drinks) so would recommend getting wine or beer there

I really enjoy coming here for Awadhi cuisine which I sometimes crave ever since I went to Lucknow where I had the real deal. I recommend sticking to the Awadhi Specialties which are unique and cannot be found in other Indian restaurants. Galouti kebab, dum pukht biryani, and shahi tukda are at the top my suggestions.
Very good Indian food

Food was excellent the second time around and service was up to par.

Creative refined Indian

Super cozy, amazing food, beautiful decor, and good service. Order the garlic naan, the veggie samosas (some of the best I’ve ever had!), and the coconut chicken dish. The coconut shrimp curry is also incredible! Everything was delicious. It fills up (downstairs and upstairs) at dinner time so make a reservation if you’re going at a busy time. Good date spot! Feels fancy without being wayyy overly priced. Far better than your average Indian spot. Much more authentic and creative dishes.

Excellent Indian food. Biryani dish was well prepared and tasty. The chicken entree with coconut gravy was superb. Will definitely eat here again. Make reservations. Update. Took a group of eight for dinner to celebrate my birthday and each and everyone enjoyed the food.
Not a good place to spend your money and appetite. Really bad service. It seems fancy out..just bulshit
Great food and decor, staff was very friendly and management was very detailed orientated.

Drlicious food and great service. Courteous staff too

My favorite Indian food in NY. The Khaas Korma, lamb sag, minced lamb appetizer, and vegetable biryani are my favorites. The flavors and quality of ingredients is on a whole other level compared to other Indian places in the neighborhood. Go here
Tasty food. Well presented. Worth a visit if you like Indian cuisine.
Great little Indian spot. A little far from uptown but if you’re looking for good food it’s worth the cab ride.
Good food. Good service.

Decent food. Expensive. Not the best but not disappointing as well.
Love this little small place. Gets crowded after 6pm, but excellent staff and food. A must try!

I come here at least once a month. I especially like the chicken biryani. The restaurant itself is cozy and the staff is very nice.
Our favorite Indian restaurant in the city! Junoon has a Michelin star but to me the food here tastes better (though the space is less fancy for sure). Great vegetarian options.
Great food, ok service, nice indian sit down restaurant on the UWS

The place is not perfect , the waiters look so busy running around fast moving but with no service. I have order the lunch special, it took them 30mins between the appetizer and the main dish. They pay more attention in keeping your glass of water full in stead of serving food lol.

Awadh serves some amazing Awadhi cuisine and are known for their slow cookes curries and bryanis, as well as their kababs and mughlai food. Being from Lucknow, I am a snob when it comes to good Mughlai/Awadhi food. This is the place so go and check it out. Loved nalli ki nihari, goat biryani, galavat kababs and malai kofta. Chicken seekh kababs were superb too.
Very nice food and very friendly staff. Room looked pretty and the portion we got to eat was lovely made and definetly enough.
Beyond excellent. Great atmosphere.

Had ordered the chicken tikka masala and everything tasted excellent including the delicious garlic naan, however at the end I noticed my stomach started hurting and some of the chicken wasnt fully cooked. Ended up having stomach pain all night ugh. Would have returned to this place of the stomach pain wasnt the case. Going to stick with banjara/darbar.  Ambiance: amazing Staff: very friendly Food: chicken tikka masala got me good Garlic naan= AMAZING!!!
Very good Indian food with a lot of choice, perfect service

One of the best Indian restaurants in NYC. Try the Lobster so good. Friendly staff, great drinks and good sized portions. Price for portions is a great deal.

Within just one dining experience, Awadh distinguished itself as one of the best Indian Restaurants I have visited. The menu items at Awadh are not necessarily what you'd find at your typical Indian establishment; that is because the culinary staff have made it their priority to celebrate the food of a specific region that showcases sophisticated, rich flavors that are mild but booming. As I observed other guests around me, I could not help but notice the unique and exciting presentation of the meals, food that is art to both the eyes and the taste buds. Everything I tasted surpassed by expectations and certainly will keep me coming back for more in the future.  It is important to note that the service here was also exceptional. The staff were welcoming, generous, and sincere. All this being said, I am happy to highly recommend Awadh to friends, family, strangers alike.

Oh dear Sweet & Sara, gift to vegans and others everywhere : ) !  I used to purchase Sweet & Sara marshmallows online from a vegan food supplier, after learning that (horrors!!!) "real" marshmallows were made from really nasty parts of our four-legged friends. Little did I know that Sweet & Sara's heavenly animal-free puffs were made right here in the NYC area~!  So, a few months ago I purchased a Groupon for Sweet & Sara, having known them and loved them for ages. And yes--when I went to redeem the Groupon online, I discovered that the shipping costs were rather atrocious. Seeing as how you can pick your goodies up at the factory in LIC if you are so inclined, I decided to do just that. Oh, treats upon treats!!! I got to meet the real "Sara" behind Sweet & Sara, and I'm delighted to say that she totally rocks!!!! We talked for a good long time about veganism. food politics, marshmallows, etc...then, she let me pick out my Groupon goodies from a table heaped with vegan deliciousness. Oh, the marshmallows! Oh, the s'mores! Oh, the biscotti!!!! I actually think the best thing was the vegan rice krispy treats. Oh nom nom nom to it all!!!!  I rode the 7 train home in a state of vegan sweet heaven....
